</boilerplate><sections><clause id="_the_relation_between_the_numbers_iim_r_and_iib_j" obligation="normative">
<title>The relation between the numbers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(M)_r</asciimath></stem> and <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>B</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(B)_j</asciimath></stem></title>
<p id="_b3c3ae70-4905-e4bd-f3e2-0d2f6336217d">In our recent study <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> on alternate sums of powers of integers, i.e. of sums of the type</p>

<formula id="eq1"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="double-struck">
        <mi>Z</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>n</mi>
      </munderover>
      <msup>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mo>−</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>j</mi>
      </msup>
    </mrow>
    <msup>
      <mi>j</mi>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msup>
    <mo>, </mo>
    <mtext> with </mtext>
    <mi>r</mi>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mn>1</mn>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mn>2</mn>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_rZZ_n = sum_(j=1)^n (-1)^j j^r, " with " r = 1,2,...,</asciimath></stem></formula>

<p id="_d0c26d69-63a5-fda2-a991-905ddcf3ab3e">it was shown that they can be expressed in the form</p>

<formula id="eq2"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="double-struck">
        <mi>Z</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mo>−</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
      </munderover>
      <msub>
        <mtext/>
        <mi>r</mi>
      </msub>
    </mrow>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>μ</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
    <msup>
      <mi>t</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msup>
    <mo>+</mo>
    <mfrac>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mn>2</mn>
    </mfrac>
    <msup>
      <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mo>−</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msup>
    <msup>
      <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>t</mi>
        <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msup>
    <mo>,</mo>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_rZZ_n = sum_(j=1)^(r-1) ""_r ii(mu)_j t^j + 1/2 (-1)^n (2t)^r,</asciimath></stem></formula>

<p id="_3304e346-bf7b-da88-8f04-00afa72b9c5c">where <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>t</mi>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
      <mo>[</mo>
      <mfrac>
        <mrow>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mo>+</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mn>2</mn>
      </mfrac>
      <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>t = [(n+1)/2]</asciimath></stem> is given by the number of terms in <xref target="eq1"/>, while <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>μ</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_r ii(mu)_j</asciimath></stem> are coefficients that have been tabulated.</p>

<p id="_46146918-dc1f-d214-93a1-afec593d49b9">We found that these coefficients can be expressed by the “basic” integers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>≡</mo>
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>μ</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mn>1</mn>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(M)_r -= ""_r ii(mu)_1</asciimath></stem>, since</p>

<formula id="eq3"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>μ</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mfrac>
      <mrow>
        <msup>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mrow>
            <mi>j</mi>
            <mo>−</mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mi>!</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mi>!</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mo>−</mo>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>+</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>!</mi>
      </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mrow>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>−</mo>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mtext> for </mtext>
    <mi>r</mi>
    <mo>&gt;</mo>
    <mi>j</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_r ii(mu)_j = (2^(j-1)r!)/(j!(r-j+1)!) ii(M)_(r-j+1)," for " r &gt; j</asciimath></stem></formula>

<p id="_aa062cb6-1b4c-fdb0-de9a-9d58e6168bdf">The alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/>, written in powers of <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>t</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>t</asciimath></stem>, thus begins for <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>r</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>r</asciimath></stem> even with</p>

<formula id="eq4"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="double-struck">
        <mi>Z</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <mi>t</mi>
    <mo>+</mo>
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>μ</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mn>2</mn>
    </msub>
    <msup>
      <mi>t</mi>
      <mn>2</mn>
    </msup>
    <mo>+</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_rZZ_n = ii(M)_rt + ""_r ii(mu)_2t^2 + ...,</asciimath></stem></formula>

<p id="_77e46907-274a-764a-ddbb-f5c89207a5cb">whereas for <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>r</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>r</asciimath></stem> odd there is no term proportional to <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>t</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>t</asciimath></stem>.</p>

<p id="_82800867-733a-4028-677e-8e96d4b91284">It appears that the numbers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(M)_r</asciimath></stem> play a role similar to that of the well-known Bernoulli numbers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>B</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(B)_j</asciimath></stem> which occur in the study of the sums</p>

<formula id="eq5"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>S</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>≡</mo>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>n</mi>
      </munderover>
      <msup>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mi>r</mi>
      </msup>
    </mrow>
    <mo>.</mo>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_r ii(S)_n -= sum_(j=1)^n j^r.</asciimath></stem></formula>

<p id="_216b38f8-88ac-c1c2-2ecc-7902bd8034f0">Some similarities between the numbers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>B</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(B)_j</asciimath></stem> and <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(M)_r</asciimath></stem> have already been noted in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>, but it has not been possible to establish a clear link between the two series. It is the purpose of the present Note to make up for this deficiency. Some familiarity with <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> will make the reading easier.</p>

<p id="_c825430d-3e91-e626-5a22-a92c1fee067a">The idea is to use the fact that the numbers <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>M</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>ii(M)_r</asciimath></stem> are the coefficients of <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>t</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>t</asciimath></stem>, as shown in <xref target="eq4"/>. If we can subdivide <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="double-struck">
        <mi>Z</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_rZZ_n</asciimath></stem> into a sum of contributions of type <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="italic">
        <mi>S</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_r ii(S)_n</asciimath></stem> and determine the coefficients of the linear terms <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>t</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>t</asciimath></stem> (in which the Bernoulli numbers occur), it must be possible to obtain the required relation by comparison of the respective coefficients.</p>

<p id="_d90ae285-a6b6-b7cc-c697-2a8280e4a551">Let us begin by decomposing the alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/> in a suitable way — the very  rearrangement we tried to avoid in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. Since <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>n</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>n</asciimath></stem> is even, we can put <stem type="MathML" block="false"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="false">
    <mi>n</mi>
    <mo>/</mo>
    <mn>2</mn>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mi>t</mi>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>n//2 = t</asciimath></stem>. Then</p>

<formula id="eq6"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <msub>
      <mtext/>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msub>
    <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="double-struck">
        <mi>Z</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>t</mi>
      </munderover>
      <msup>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>r</mi>
      </msup>
    </mrow>
    <mo>−</mo>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>t</mi>
      </munderover>
      <msup>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>−</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>r</mi>
      </msup>
    </mrow>
  </mstyle>
</math>
<asciimath>""_rZZ_n = sum_(j=1)^t (2j)^r - sum_(j=1)^t (2j-1)^r</asciimath></stem></formula>

<formula id="_7048015a-27ee-ccc8-d180-a375df04a1d3" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML" block="true"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <mo>=</mo>
    <msup>
      <mn>2</mn>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msup>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>t</mi>
      </munderover>
      <msup>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mi>r</mi>
      </msup>
    </mrow>
    <mo>−</mo>
    <msup>
      <mn>2</mn>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msup>
    <msup>
      <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mfrac>
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mn>2</mn>
        </mfrac>
        <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <mi>r</mi>
    </msup>
    <mrow>
      <munderover>
        <mo>∑</mo>
        <mrow>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mi>t</mi>
      </munderover>
      <mrow>
        <munderover>
          <mo>∑</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>=</mo>
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
          <mi>r</mi>
        </munderover>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mtable>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mi>r</mi>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mi>k</mi>
              </mtd>
